Evaluation and choice: Between the two, Back in Black aligns more tightly with those priorities. Its midrange‑forward, crunchy guitars and riff‑led 3–5 minute songs put guitar and lead voice at the center of the music, matching my preference for guitar‑driven, vocal‑forward material. The description emphasizes gravelly vocals, tight driving drums, punchy transient‑preserving mastering and a muscular low‑mid presence that deliver “live‑immediate” playback — this maps directly to my desire for punchy, breathing mixes and vocal immediacy rather than glossy polish. The album is described as artist‑focused in sequencing, which satisfies my LP‑level sequencing preference and the desire for records that reward repeated attentive, start‑to‑finish listening. Crucially, Back in Black’s raw grit and resistance to glossy sheen matches my dislike of over‑polished, radio‑flattened production.
Why I reject Decade: Decade is presented as a Classic Rock/AOR anthology with multi‑layered guitars and keyboards, lush vocal harmonies, and loud‑but‑clear mastering. While it scores points for tight sequencing and preserved dynamics, it also emphasizes keyboards and an AOR/anthology context. That raises two concerns relative to my dislikes: (1) the presence of prominent keyboards and AOR production risks the synth‑dated or glossy sheen I try to avoid, and (2) being an anthology format—even one said to have good sequencing—falls closer to the type of multi‑era/compilation risk I dislike (sonic unevenness and a compilation feel that can dilute a single artist’s theatrical vocal arc). Decade’s lush harmonies and spacious reverbs sound well produced, but they tilt toward polished, studio‑gloss territory and layered AOR textures rather than the raw, vocal‑immediate, guitar‑driven punch I prioritize.
Net: Back in Black better satisfies the key, non‑negotiable elements in my self‑introduction — upfront, gritty vocals; guitar‑first arrangements; punchy, transient‑preserving mixes; and cohesive artist sequencing — so it is the better fit.

